You can import java.lang.Math, and then use Math.pow(a, b), the code can look like this:

    public static void main(String args[])
    {
        double a = 30;
        double sum = 0;
        for(int b = 1; b &lt;= 9; b += 2) { 
            sum += Math.pow(a, b)
        }
        System.out.println(sum);
    }

Java&#39;s `Math.pow` will be useful ([documentation](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Math.html#pow-double-double-))

You also should not be modifying `x` as you go (since you always want the _same_ number raised to varying powers), but rather have a separate variable to collect the sum.

In the end, it should look something like this:

```lang-java
public class MyClass {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        System.out.println(calculateExp(3.0));
    }

    public static double calculateExp(double x) {
        double total = 0.0;
        for(int i = 1; i &lt;= 9; i += 2) {
            total += Math.pow(x, i);
        }
        return total;
    }
}
```

EDIT: if you&#39;re not allowed to use Math.pow, you can calculate `x^i` manually with another loop, like this:

```lang-java
public class MyClass {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        System.out.println(calculateExp(3.0));
    }

    public static double calculateExp(double x) {
        double total = 0.0;
        for(int i = 1; i &lt;= 9; i += 2) {
            double x_to_i = 1.0;
            for(int j = 0; j &lt; i; j++) {
                x_to_i *= x;
            }
            total += x_to_i;
        }
        return total;
    }
}

